node.title: Orban, visiting Moscow, is accused of stoking acrimony with the E.U.
node.description: Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary is perhaps the closest ally of President Vladimir V. Putin within the 27-member bloc.

node.title: In one week, Florida fishermen reel in 2 rifles — and a man's body
node.description: A boy and his grandpa pulled two .50-caliber Barrett sniper rifles out of a canal near Miami days after a fisherman hooked a human body in a central Florida lake.

node.title: Year after military takeover in Myanmar, hope for democracy clings on
node.description: The generals who arrested civilian leaders and quashed huge street protests with deadly force are undoubtedly in control and the fight for freedom is down, but it's not out.

node.title: Whoopi Goldberg apologizes for saying Holocaust "not about race"
node.description: Goldberg said on "The View" on Monday that the Holocaust, which resulted in the deaths of more than 6 million people, was about "how people treat each other."

node.title: As U.S. and Russia argue, war is already a reality for many Ukrainians
node.description: Moscow and Washington disagree on everything from which side is the aggressor, to who has responded to who, but in eastern Ukraine, the question isn't when war will start, but if it will ever end.

node.title: Judge rejects federal plea deal in Ahmaud Arbery's killing
node.description: Arbery's parents had denounced the proposed deal for Travis and Gregory McMichael.

node.title: Iran purportedly executes 2 gay men over sodomy charges
node.description: A human rights organization says the men were hanged at a prison after 6 years on death row in Iran, where homosexuality is officially banned.

node.title: Joe Rogan responds to Neil Young and Spotify
node.description: Rogan said he books the guests himself, and talked about what he can do "to balance things out."

node.title: A cause of America's labor shortage: Millions with long COVID
node.description: As many as 30% of people with COVID develop the long-term illness, with many sufferers struggling to return to work.

node.title: What's behind the push for a fourth stimulus check
node.description: IRS has distributed almost 170 million payments. But hardship remains widespread as the Omicron variant spreads.

node.title: Second day of bomb threats against several historically Black schools
node.description: Some, including Howard University, got them both days. No explosions have been reported.

node.title: Lightning bolt stretching 477 miles over 3 U.S. states sets record
node.description: 2 new records, which are not linked to climate change, were spotted and confirmed thanks to new satellite tracking technology.

node.title: City urges residents near blazing fertilizer plant to evacuate
node.description: Police in Winston-Salem, North Carolina says there could be an explosion at the site. They said first responders were "pleading" with nearby residents to get out.

node.title: An 8-Year-Old Wrote a Book and Hid It on a Library Shelf. It’s a Hit.
node.description: Dillon Helbig, a second-grader from Idaho, wrote an 81-page book about his “Crismis” adventures. Now other children want to write stories.

node.title: Winter Storm Poised to Hit From Albuquerque to Detroit, Bringing Bitter Cold
node.description: New Mexico, Texas and other areas unaccustomed to snow, ice and freezing wind chills are bracing for days of frigid weather.

node.title: UCLA switches to remote learning due to threats
node.description: The threats reportedly include references to mass shootings. The switch comes only a day after the school had returned to in-person classes following a span of remote learning due to the COVID-19 surge.

node.title: How to Ski Blind
node.description: Only use guides who lead rather than follow you. At the top of the run, ask them for a play-by-play so you know what’s coming.

node.title: Write It in Garamond
node.description: Creative output of any kind depends upon a steady stream of tiny self-delusions. A different font helps me believe in my own words.

node.title: Is It OK That I’m OK With Our Mom’s Adultery?
node.description: The magazine’s Ethicist columnist on when disclosing a secret is a betrayal — and more.

node.title: A Town That Saved a Mountain, and a Mountain That Saved a Town
node.description: After the Ascutney ski resort in Vermont closed because of erratic snowfall and mismanagement, it threatened to take with it the nearby town of West Windsor. The community took the situation into its own hands.

node.title: On the Cajun Coast, a Chef Grapples With Threats to a Seafood Tradition
node.description: From her New Orleans restaurant, Melissa Martin sees the environmental damage that could end the region’s rich culture of food and fishing.

node.title: Attenborough, WHO, Tsikhanouskaya among nominees for Nobel Peace Prize
node.description: British nature broadcaster David Attenborough, the World Health Organisation and Belarusian dissident Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya are among the nominees for this year's Nobel Peace Prize.

node.title: Ron Brierley's jail sentence slashed due to declining health
node.description: Disgraced New Zealand businessman Ron Brierley has had his prison sentence reduced in Australia for possessing child sex abuse images.

node.title: Bluff your way through the Beijing Winter Olympics
node.description: Can't swack your pretzel from your melon when it comes to the Winter Olympics?

node.title: US states, other nations back Mexico's lawsuit against gun makers
node.description: Thirteen US states and two Latin America and Caribbean nations have thrown their support behind Mexico's lawsuit accusing major US gun makers of facilitating weapons trafficking to drug cartels.

node.title: Myanmar activists vow to defy junta with strike on coup anniversary
node.description: Myanmar's military rulers are threatening to jail anti-coup protesters who take part in a "silent strike" as the US, Britain and Canada impose new sanctions.

node.title: Police appeal for information on missing Masterton man
node.description: Police are concerned about a man missing from Masterton since Monday.

node.title: Three die in road crashes in Waikato
node.description: Three people have been killed in crashes in the Waikato district today, two at Eureka and one in Waitoa.

node.title: Murupara doctor suspended from Friday
node.description: Murupara's GP of 30 years standing, Dr Bernard Conlon, is to be suspended from practising medicine as of Friday.

node.title: After the peak: What's next after the Omicron wave turns?
node.description: As New Zealand waits for the predicted surge in Omicron cases, Australia may have reached the peak of its wave. The ABC's Maani Truu looks at what's in store for Australia next.
